<div id="review_721202623" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/721202623" />
    <a title="Jimmy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1325473-jimmy"><img alt="Jimmy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1364565813p2/1325473.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/721202623?book_show_action=true">Sep 16, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jimmy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jimmy" href="/user/show/1325473-jimmy">Jimmy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Jimmy by: </span>
      CS, SUR
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1325473-jimmy?shelf=year-2000s">year-2000s</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1325473-jimmy?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1325473-jimmy?shelf=male">male</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1325473-jimmy?shelf=and-a-half-stars">and-a-half-stars</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer721202623" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7937532590862030674">A long time ago I had decided not to ever read anything by Dave Eggers. That was because he had written an atrocity of a book called &apos;A Hearbreaking Work of Staggering Genius&apos;. It was self indulgent, self conscious posturing, using literary gimmicks in a way that I found wholly inauthentic. This was AGES ago, though, so don&apos;t ask me for specific complaints. I don&apos;t remember them.<br/><br/>Anyway, about a month ago, a friend was reading Zeitoun and finished it in about a day, then lent it to another friend</span>
  <span id="freeText7937532590862030674" style="display:none">A long time ago I had decided not to ever read anything by Dave Eggers. That was because he had written an atrocity of a book called 'A Hearbreaking Work of Staggering Genius'. It was self indulgent, self conscious posturing, using literary gimmicks in a way that I found wholly inauthentic. This was AGES ago, though, so don't ask me for specific complaints. I don't remember them.<br /><br />Anyway, about a month ago, a friend was reading Zeitoun and finished it in about a day, then lent it to another friend who finished it in about the same time. They told me briefly about the book, and against my earlier decision, I borrowed the book. I put it in a pile of books to be read later.<br /><br />That 'later' was yesterday. I started it and I couldn't stop. I've got to give it to Dave Eggers in that there was no Dave Eggers in here. The reason this book succeeded was that he was able to step aside and let Zeitoun and Kathy tell their stories, using the plainest style possible to convey the most heartbreaking, sickening, and devastating episodes.<br /><br />I don't know how much of the story I should reveal... it's better that you just read the book. But I'll just say that it's based on true accounts of a family who survived hurricane Katrina in New Orleans, and then survived many other more unpredictable trials. The book as a whole--its before, during, and after of events described--perfectly encapsulates my love/hate relationship with this country.<br /><br />I urge you to read this (and especially if you would never normally read Dave Eggers). If you give it 40 pages of your attention, I guarantee you will finish the whole thing in a day or 2.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7937532590862030674" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


