    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_337913587" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/337913587" />
    <a title="knig" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6163905-knig"><img alt="knig" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/337913587?book_show_action=true">May 27, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="knig" class="user" itemprop="url" name="knig" href="/user/show/6163905-knig">knig</a>
      </span>

          added it




          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to knig by: </span>
      <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/219570054">http://www.goodreads.com/review/show/...</a>
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6163905-knig?shelf=disturbia">disturbia</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6163905-knig?shelf=2012">2012</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer337913587" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5633900270333632548">I am currently at the back end of a monster diet: 500 calories a day, all protein, no carb. I am also now a Knut Hamsun character: no body come near me, or I will eat you. Literally. Things are baaad. And so, last night, I caved in, a bought a Penguin at the kiosk. Normally, I wouldn’t touch it with a barge poll. Haute cuisine it ain’t, and frankly, I’ve never seen anyone under 300 pounds eating one. But, this was no time for debating the finer points of degustation. Or any other points, for tha</span>
  <span id="freeText5633900270333632548" style="display:none">I am currently at the back end of a monster diet: 500 calories a day, all protein, no carb. I am also now a Knut Hamsun character: no body come near me, or I will eat you. Literally. Things are baaad. And so, last night, I caved in, a bought a Penguin at the kiosk. Normally, I wouldn’t touch it with a barge poll. Haute cuisine it ain’t, and frankly, I’ve never seen anyone under 300 pounds eating one. But, this was no time for debating the finer points of degustation. Or any other points, for that matter: the Penguin was the only thing that existed in the world at that point in time. My kingdom for a Penguin sort of thing. Well. The sugar rush from that very first bite was like a shockwave. I could feel my adrenaline screaming . A chemical revolution was in the churn.<br /><br />This is exactly how this book felt. On the back of a long steady diet of slipstream, surrealism and PoMo, this complete change of reading tactic threw me in a tailspin. I don’t know if its a good book or a bad book, I can’t even rate it, because it may very well be my ‘rebound’ literary companion, but. I was on the edge of my seat the entire time, all systems on high alert. Helped by the fact that, although I knew it was non-fiction, I didn’t know the story at all, and so the electrifying suspense of Zeitoun’s odyssey, which could very well have ended with a trip up to the Pearly Gates, had me spellbound.<br /><br />More so than his personal ordeal, though, which was truly horrific, I was gobsmacked at what can only be described as the ‘failed state’ tactics of the various US government agencies in dealing with the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina in New Orleans. Whilst clearly this account is heavily biased, and certainly there may be other stories of the efficiency, courage and sensitivity in dealing with the psychological and physical debris ensuing, the fact remains that what happened to Zeitoun and almost two thousand other (mostly African American) detainees at the time is simply inexcusable. Interred without provocation, without charges and without recourse to the legal system at all, denied medical care, denied a phonecall and repeatedly tortured, Zeitoun (and fellow inmates) simply vanished in the penal system without a trace. Just like Alice down the rabbit hole. No one, and I mean, no one knew where they were. In Zeitoun’s case, a chance missionary took pity on him and contacted his wife. Subsequently, a family friend who happened to be a lawyer, intervened and with the support of his resourceful wife, he was freed on bail . His other cell companions, who did not have such ‘personal’ support, languished inside for up to a year. <br /><br />Absolutely riveting stuff, horrifying, haunting, sinister. Shocking.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="5633900270333632548" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


